2 HOUSE BILL 297
1 SECTION 1. BE IT ENACTED BY THE GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF MARYLAND,
2 That the Laws of Maryland read as follows:
3 Article – Labor and Employment
4 11–808.
5 (a) An individual may obtain a high school diploma by examination as provided
6 in this section if the individual:
7 (1) has not obtained a high school diploma;
8 (2) resides in this State; and
9 (3) except as provided in subsection (b) of this section:
10 (i) is not subject to compulsory school attendance under § 7–301 of
11 the Education Article; and
12 (ii) has withdrawn from a regular full–time public or private school
13 program.
14 (b) An individual is not subject to the requirements of subsection (a)(3) of this
15 section if the individual participates in:
16 (1) a GED Option Program administered by the State Department of
17 Education that creates a pathway to a high school diploma by examination for currently
18 enrolled high school English language learner students under the age of 21 years who have
19 experienced interrupted education and have a lower level of English proficiency than their
20 peers; OR
21 (2) THE GED OPTION PILOT PROGRAM ESTABLISHED UNDER §
22 11–808.1 OF THIS SUBTITLE.
23 11–808.1.
24 (A) IN THIS SECTION, “PILOT PROGRAM” MEANS THE GED OPTION PILOT
25 PROGRAM.
26 (B) (1) THERE IS A GED OPTION PILOT PROGRAM IN THE STATE.
27 (2) THE PURPOSE OF THE PILOT PROGRAM IS TO EXPAND THE GED
28 OPTION PROGRAM TO STUDENTS BEYOND ENGLISH LANGUAGE LEARNERS IN
29 SELECTED SCHOOL DISTRICTS TO ENSURE THAT THE STUDENTS HAVE A PATHWAY

HOUSE BILL 297 3
1 TO OBTAIN A HIGH SCHOOL DIPLOMA AND ARE PREPARED TO ENTER
2 POSTSECONDARY PROGRAMMING OR THE WORKFORCE.
3 (C) THE PILOT PROGRAM SHALL BEGIN IN THE 2027–2028 SCHOOL YEAR
4 AND SHALL CONTINUE FOR 2 SCHOOL YEARS.
5 (D) THE DEPARTMENT:
6 (1) IN CONSULTATION WITH THE STATE DEPARTMENT OF
7 EDUCATION AND THE PUBLIC SCHOOL SUPERINTENDENTS’ ASSOCIATION OF
8 MARYLAND, SHALL DEVELOP CRITERIA, INCLUDING RECOGNITION OF GEOGRAPHIC
9 DIVERSITY, FOR THE SELECTION OF AT LEAST THREE LOCAL SCHOOL SYSTEMS TO
10 PARTICIPATE IN THE PILOT PROGRAM; AND
11 (2) IN CONSULTATION WITH THE STATE DEPARTMENT OF
12 EDUCATION, SHALL USE THE CRITERIA DEVELOPED UNDER ITEM (1) OF THIS
13 SUBSECTION TO SELECT AT LEAST THREE LOCAL SCHOOL SYSTEMS TO PARTICIPATE
14 IN THE PILOT PROGRAM.
15 (E) EACH COUNTY SUPERINTENDENT FROM A PARTICIPATING LOCAL
16 SCHOOL SYSTEM MAY SELECT UP TO 150 STUDENTS TO PARTICIPATE IN THE PILOT
17 PROGRAM.
18 (F) A STUDENT SELECTED TO PARTICIPATE IN THE PILOT PROGRAM:
19 (1) MAY BEGIN THE GED OPTION PROGRAM WHEN THE STUDENT IS
20 AT LEAST 17 YEARS OLD;
21 (2) MUST BE AT SIGNIFICANT RISK OF NOT SUCCESSFULLY
22 COMPLETING HIGH SCHOOL; AND
23 (3) SHALL TAKE THE HIGH SCHOOL DIPLOMA BY EXAMINATION
24 BEFORE THE CONCLUSION OF THE GED OPTION PROGRAM.
25 (G) THE DEPARTMENT AND THE STATE DEPARTMENT OF EDUCATION
26 SHALL EXPLORE OPTIONS FOR EXPANDING THE GED OPTION PROGRAM BASED ON
27 RESULTS OF THE PILOT PROGRAM.
28 (H) (1) ON OR BEFORE DECEMBER 1, 2028, AND DECEMBER 1, 2029, THE
29 DEPARTMENT AND THE STATE DEPARTMENT OF EDUCATION JOINTLY SHALL
30 REPORT TO THE GOVERNOR AND, IN ACCORDANCE WITH § 2–1257 OF THE STATE
31 GOVERNMENT ARTICLE, THE GENERAL ASSEMBLY REGARDING THE
32 EFFECTIVENESS OF THE PILOT PROGRAM.

4 HOUSE BILL 297
1 (2) THE REPORT REQUIRED UNDER PARAGRAPH (1) OF THIS
2 SUBSECTION SHALL INCLUDE:
3 (I) THE NUMBER OF STUDENTS PARTICIPATING IN THE PILOT
4 PROGRAM FROM EACH PARTICIPATING LOCAL SCHOOL SYSTEM;
5 (II) FEEDBACK FROM EDUCATORS, STUDENTS, AND PARENTS OF
6 STUDENTS PARTICIPATING IN THE PILOT PROGRAM ON WAYS TO IMPROVE THE
7 GED OPTION PROGRAM;
8 (III) THE NUMBER OF STUDENTS WHO EARNED A HIGH SCHOOL
9 DIPLOMA AS A RESULT OF COMPLETING THE PILOT PROGRAM; AND
10 (IV) AN EVALUATION OF THE PILOT PROGRAM AND THE GED
11 OPTION PROGRAM WITH ANY RECOMMENDATIONS FOR IMPROVEMENTS.
12 (I) THE DEPARTMENT AND THE STATE DEPARTMENT OF EDUCATION
13 JOINTLY MAY ADOPT REGULATIONS TO IMPLEMENT THE PILOT PROGRAM.
14 SECTION 2. AND BE IT FURTHER ENACTED, That the Laws of Maryland read
15 as follows:
16 Article – Labor and Employment
17 11–810.
18 (A) IN THIS SECTION, “MDIPLOMAWORKS PATHWAY” MEANS AN
19 ALTERNATIVE PATHWAY TO EARN A HIGH SCHOOL DIPLOMA IN THE STATE.
20 (B) THE MDIPLOMAWORKS PATHWAY IS A METHOD TO RECOGNIZE AND
21 CERTIFY HIGH SCHOOL DIPLOMA ACHIEVEMENT THROUGH DEMONSTRATED
22 ACADEMIC AND CAREER COMPETENCIES, INCLUDING WORKFORCE EXPERIENCE.
23 (C) AN INDIVIDUAL MAY OBTAIN A HIGH SCHOOL DIPLOMA THROUGH THE
24 MDIPLOMAWORKS PATHWAY IF THE INDIVIDUAL:
25 (1) HAS NOT OBTAINED A HIGH SCHOOL DIPLOMA;
26 (2) RESIDES IN THE STATE;
27 (3) IS NOT SUBJECT TO THE COMPULSORY SCHOOL ATTENDANCE
28 REQUIREMENT UNDER § 7–301 OF THE EDUCATION ARTICLE; AND

HOUSE BILL 297 5
1 (4) HAS WITHDRAWN FROM A REGULAR FULL–TIME PUBLIC OR
2 PRIVATE SCHOOL PROGRAM.
3 (D) TO EARN A HIGH SCHOOL DIPLOMA THROUGH THE MDIPLOMAWORKS
4 PATHWAY, AN INDIVIDUAL SHALL DEMONSTRATE EQUIVALENCY TO A MARYLAND
5 HIGH SCHOOL DIPLOMA BY COMPLETION OF A COMBINATION OF THE FOLLOWING
6 COMPONENTS AS APPROVED BY THE DEPARTMENT:
7 (1) EARNING INDUSTRY–RECOGNIZED CREDENTIALS;
8 (2) DEMONSTRATING FOUNDATIONAL ACADEMIC SKILLS THROUGH
9 FORMAL ASSESSMENTS;
10 (3) COMPLETING CAREER AND TECHNICAL EDUCATION
11 COURSEWORK; AND
12 (4) COMPLETING AN ON–THE–JOB LEARNING EXPERIENCE.
13 (E) A HIGH SCHOOL DIPLOMA SHALL BE AWARDED TO AN INDIVIDUAL WHO
14 COMPLETES THE MDIPLOMAWORKS PATHWAY IN ACCORDANCE WITH THE
15 REGULATIONS ADOPTED BY THE SECRETARY AND THE STATE BOARD OF
16 EDUCATION.
17 SECTION 3. AND BE IT FURTHER ENACTED, That this Act shall take effect
18 October 1, 2026. Section 1 of this Act shall remain effective for a period of 4 years and, at
19 the end of September 30, 2030, Section 1 of this Act, with no further action required by the
20 General Assembly, shall be abrogated and of no further force and effect.

